&gt; &gt;&nbsp;&nbsp; * BeforeClass -- annotation for methods to be run
&gt; before all tests in a&lt;br /&gt;
&gt; &gt; class&lt;br /&gt;
&gt; &gt;&nbsp;&nbsp; * After -- annotation for methods to be run after
&gt; each test method&lt;br /&gt;
&gt; &gt;&nbsp;&nbsp; * AfterClass -- annotation for methods to be run
&gt; after all tests in a&lt;br /&gt;
&gt; &gt; class&lt;br /&gt;
&gt; &gt;&nbsp;&nbsp; * Ignore -- annotation for test methods that are
&gt; temporarily not to be run&lt;br /&gt;
&gt; &gt;&nbsp;&nbsp; * Test -- annotation for methods that are to be run
&gt; as tests&lt;br /&gt;
&gt; &gt;&nbsp;&nbsp; * Assert -- assertion methods, expected to be used
&gt; via static import&lt;br /&gt;
&gt; &lt;br /&gt;
&gt; I think Before and After don&#39;t tell the programmer enough about the
&gt; context. As you wrote, Before is an &#39;annotation for methods to be run
&gt; before each test method&#39;, so I would call it BeforeTestMethod. It&#39;s
&gt; longer but much clearer. When I read my first JUnit 4 Test, &#39;Before&#39;
&gt; made me think &#39;before what?&#39;. I was quite(although not entirely) sure
&gt; that it had got to do with the tests but I had no idea if it meant run
&gt; once for a class, once for every test method or just once for all
&gt; tests. I had to look it up to be sure. &lt;br /&gt;
&gt; &lt;br /&gt;
&gt; For this reason I think that all annotations above should at least
&gt; contain the word &#39;Test&#39;. &lt;br /&gt;
&gt; &lt;br /&gt;
